(Tony Karumba, AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Nairobi - Herders and large-scale farmers in parts of Kenya's Rift Valley are desperately waiting for seasonal rains to ease the prolonged drought and the current conflict over grazing land in which more than 30 people have died.Kenya's military and police have been working for a month to disarm and drive the hundreds of herders and their animals out of ranches they've invaded, but their actions appear to have escalated the violence.The Laikipia Ranchers' Association says when the military and police drive nomadic herders from one sprawling ranch they move into another ranch.Martin Evans, the ranchers' association chairperson said on Monday that politicians campaigning for positions in the August elections are inciting the herders to invade the ranches saying that it is their ancestral land.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.